{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d9d33afc-5ccb-45fe-bd85-151ecd4de40d","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2, which fully supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init via [TestInitialize]\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        var result = await _service.DoWorkAsync();\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup\n    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — inject `TestContext` and do sync setup. A new instance is created per test.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — use for `async` setup that can't go in a constructor.\n- **`IAsyncDisposable`/`IDisposable`** — preferred over `[TestCleanup]` for resource cleanup.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]`** — still available for one-time static setup shared across all tests in the class.\n\nThe old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property-setter pattern still works but constructor injection is the modern, idiomatic approach in MSTest v3+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d72a718f-64be-4405-9938-89a157a68e86","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), constructor injection for `TestContext` is supported. Let me provide the recommended pattern.\n\nIn MSTest v3+:\n- You can inject `TestContext` via the constructor (no need for the property setter pattern)\n- For synchronous init, use the constructor\n- For async init, use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method\n- There's also `[ClassInitialize]` and `[AssemblyInitialize]` for broader scopes\n\nLet me give a clear, accurate answer.","outputTokens":570,"requestId":"602B:20684E:25CF44C:2868E9C:6A0311E3"},"id":"2e8a9655-5ca5-4d34-89ac-0b62e89da704","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:41:35.463Z","parentId":"f10523e8-5255-48be-a016-dfa8ab9a1276"}
